<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="dk41801_compensation_discussion_and_analysis_(cd_a)"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Compensation Discussion and Analysis (CD&amp;A)    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The CD&amp;A describes Principal Financial Group, Inc.'s Executive compensation objectives and philosophy. It also describes our 2019
compensation program and reviews the outcomes, including the Company's financial performance in 2019. Our "Named Executive Officers" in 2019 were </font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Daniel J. Houston, Chairman, President and Chief Executive
Officer.</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    Mr. Houston has overall responsibility for all businesses of the organization. He joined the company in 1984 and assumed his
current position in 2015. He previously served as President and Chief Operating Officer, overseeing all global businesses, and the Retirement and Investor Services and U.S. Insurance Solutions
segments of the organization.  </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Deanna D. Strable-Soethout, Executive Vice President and Chief Financial
Officer.</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    Ms. Strable-Soethout plays a central role in driving and managing long-term strategies for innovation-fueled company growth,
including responsibility for corporate strategy and capital markets. She joined the company in 1990 and assumed her </font></dd></dl>

<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Patrick G. Halter, Chief Executive Officer, Principal Global
Investors.</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    Mr. Halter has responsibility for overseeing the operations of Principal Global Investors, its 15 investment boutiques, and the
fund and distribution teams. He joined the company in 1984 and assumed his current position in 2018. He previously served as the Chief Operating Officer of Principal Global Investors. </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Timothy M. Dunbar, President, Global Asset

current position in 2018. He previously served as the Chief Investment Officer.  </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Luis Valdés, President, International Asset Management &amp;
Accumulation.</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    Mr. Valdés is responsible for managing the Company's operations outside of the United States in the
international asset management and accumulation segment. He has been associated with the company since 1995 and assumed his current position in 2011. He previously served as the President of Principal
Financial Group Latin America. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->
</b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b> <a name="dk1"></a>2019 Company Performance Highlights</b></font><font color="#009CCC" size="2">: </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">In 2019, Principal generated $1.4 billion of net income attributable to Principal Financial Group and $1.6 billion of non-GAAP operating earnings<sup>(1)</sup>. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">We
deployed $2.1 billion of capital in 2019, or nearly 150% of net income. We take a balanced and disciplined approach to capital deploymentwe deployed $1.2 billion of
capital through strategic acquisitions, primarily the Institutional Retirement &amp; Trust acquisition, and over $860 million of capital to shareholders through common stock dividends and
share repurchases in 2019. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Over
the course of 2019, assets under management increased $109 billion, or 17 percent, to a record $735 billion at year-end, reflecting favorable market performance and
$17 billion of net cash flow. Additionally, we ended 2019 with $146 billion of AUM in our China joint venture and $898 billion of assets under administration in the Institutional
Retirement and Trust business. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">2019
was a good year and we remain confident in our diversified business model as well as our ability to execute on our strategy and consistently deliver above market growth to deliver long-term value
for our shareholders. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Our
total shareholder return performance over the past five years was positioned well ahead of our asset manager peers and was slightly behind our insurance peers. Our total shareholder return
methodology includes the share price return and cash dividends paid during the time period. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;line-height:1pt;margin-left:18pt;"><font> </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- BLANK LINE TO FORCE PARA -->
   
</font></p><hr align="LEFT" color="#7B7C80" noshade="" size="1.0PT" width="24%"/><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> </font><p></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(1)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">This
is a non-GAAP financial measure. See non-GAAP financial measure reconciliations in Appendix D.</font></dd></dl>

<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=37,EFW="2241086",CP="PRINCIPAL FINANCIAL GROUP, INC.",DN="1",CHK=1047613,FOLIO='34',FILE='DISK124:[20ZAD1.20ZAD41801]DK41801A.;34',USER='JATHANA',CD=';2-APR-2020;14:30' -->
<a name="page_dk41801_1_35"> </a>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font size="2"><a href="#bi41801a_main_toc">Table of Contents</a></font></p>
<p align="CENTER" style="font-family:arial;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>
<img alt="GRAPHIC" height="367" src="g109387.jpg" width="574"/>
</b></font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">*</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Insurance
Peers include: Ameriprise, Lincoln National Corporation, Manulife, Metlife, Prudential, Sun Life Financial, Unum, and Voya
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">**</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Asset
Manager peers include: Affiliated Managers Group, Franklin Resources, Invesco, and T. Rowe Price </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><a name="dk41801_2019_compensation_highlights"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


2019 Compensation Highlights    <br/> </b></font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> In 2019, the Company's shareholders voted to approve the Company's Executive compensation program. Of the votes cast, 97% supported the
Executive compensation program. The Company considered the shareholders' approval of the compensation program to be approval of the Company's compensation philosophy, which has not changed since that
vote. </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> In 2019, Mr. Houston's base salary remained at $900,000. His annual incentive target increased from 350% to 375% and his long-term
incentive target increased from 750% to 775%. His Principal Financial Group Incentive Pay Plan (PrinPay Plan) payout for 2019 was $3,375,000. </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Based on our 2019 annual performance achievements, many of which are outlined above, 2019 Annual incentive payouts for Named Executive Officers
averaged 99% of target. </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Based on the Company's three-year average return on equity ("ROE")<sup>(2)</sup> and three-year average book value per
share<sup>(3)</sup> performance, the 2017-2019 Performance Based RSUs ("PSUs") vested on December 31, 2019 and 87% of the target number of shares were paid out in February 2020, according to
the established performance scale, and approval by the Human Resources Committee. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="dk41801_compensation_program_philosophy_and_policies"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Compensation Program Philosophy and Policies    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> Compensation Philosophy</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">our compensation programs are designed to:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>Attract and retain</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> talented Executives and motivate them to perform at the highest level and
contribute significantly to the Company's long-term success; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Reinforce the Company's </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>pay for performance</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> culture by making a
significant portion of total
compensation variable and by differentiating awards based on Company and individual performance in achieving short and long-term financial and strategic objectives; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Have a greater percentage of </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>compensation to be at risk</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> for
Executives who bear higher levels
of responsibility for the Company's performance; </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;line-height:1pt;margin-left:18pt;"><font> </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- BLANK LINE TO FORCE PARA -->
   
</font></p><hr align="LEFT" color="#7B7C80" noshade="" size="1.0PT" width="24%"/><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> </font><p></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(2)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Return
on equity ("ROE") is defined as (i) income from continuing operations before income taxes per the audited Consolidated Statements of Operations less
net realized/unrealized capital gains (losses) and preferred stock dividends declared during such calendar year divided by (ii) the average equity excluding other comprehensive income available
to common shareholders.
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(3)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Book
value per share is defined as total ending common equity excluding other comprehensive income divided by number of common shares outstanding end of
year.</font></dd></dl>

<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>Align the interests</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> of Executives and other stakeholders, including shareholders, customers and
employees, by having a significant portion of the Executives' compensation in stock and requiring Executives to hold stock; and </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Support important </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>corporate governance</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> principles and established
best practices. </font></dd></dl>

company performance and profitability, as outlined on pages 41-43.<br/></font>
<br/>
<font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Based on the Committee's assessment of performance, actual bonuses for 2019 averaged 99% of target as detailed on page 43.</font></td>

<tr valign="TOP">
<td style="font-family:arial;border-left:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt; " valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-left:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt; " -->


 </font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td align="CENTER" style="font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Long-Term<br/>
Incentive<br/>
Compensation</font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td align="RIGHT" style="font-family:arial;border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->


 </font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td style="font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Motivates and rewards long-term corporate performance as well as the Named Executive Officers' contribution to achieving our long-term objectives. Reinforces the link between the interests
of the Named Executive Officers and shareholders. Encourages retention.</font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td align="RIGHT" style="font-family:arial;border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->


 </font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td style="font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Each year, the Committee establishes the long-term award opportunity for each Named Executive Officer. One half of the award is granted in stock options and the other half in PSUs. Using
equal amounts of PSUs and options creates a balance between achieving operating performance objectives and increases in shareholder value.<br/></font>
<br/>
<font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The PSUs vest based on continued service (except for retirees, when they vest over time) and meeting financial objectives over a three-year period (with each three-year period treated as a "Performance Cycle"). The PSUs
granted in 2018 for the 2018-2020 Performance Cycle and in 2019 for the 2019-2021 Performance Cycle will vest based on performance scales for three-year average ROE and Pre-Tax Return on Net Revenue, each weighted 50% over the performance period.
Payout on the ROE metric is modified based on three-year Book Value per Share versus certain threshold goals. The PSUs granted in 2020 for the 2020-2022 Performance Cycle will vest based on performance scales for two-year average ROE and Pre-Tax
Return on Net Revenue, each weighted 50% over the performance period. Payout on the ROE metric will be modified based on two-year Book Value per Share versus certain threshold goals. The change in the performance period to two years is due to
accounting changes effective January 1, 2022 for publicly traded companies which may result in significant variability of reported earnings each year for companies with significant life insurance and annuity businesses. For the 2020-2022
Performance Cycle, PSUs will continue to vest at the end of the three-year Performance Cycle. Details of the program are outlined on pages 43-45.</font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">​</font></td>
<td align="RIGHT" style="font-family:arial;border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-right:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->
</font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> </font></td>
</tr>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->

<font></font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​<font>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->
</font>
</td>
<td align="RIGHT" style="line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​ <!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->
<font></font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​<font>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->
</font></td>
<td style="line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​ <!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #7B7C80 1.0pt;" -->

<td style="font-family:arial;" valign="MIDDLE"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The PSUs granted in 2017 for the 2017-2019 Performance Cycle were based on three-year average ROE and Pre-Tax Return on Net Revenue, each weighted 50%. Payout on the ROE metric is modified
based on three-year Book Value per Share versus certain threshold goals. For the 2017-2019 Performance Cycle, the awards vested and paid out at 87% of the target number of PSUs based on our ROE performance of 13.5%, Pre-Tax Return on Net Revenue of
31.5%, and Book Value per Share of $46.44.</font></td>

an employee stock purchase plan, 401(k) plan and pension plan. Named Executive Officers also participate in non-qualified retirement plans (defined benefit and defined contribution). Mr. Halter does not participate in the pension or
non-qualified retirement plans. Mr. Dunbar participated in the pension plans and non-qualified retirement plans when he was working in non-investment roles.</font></td>

<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="dm41801_how_we_make_compensation_decisions"> </a>
<a name="toc_dm41801_2"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


How We Make Compensation Decisions    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Human Resources Committee Involvement </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The Human Resources Committee </font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Oversees the development and administration of the Company's compensation and benefits policies and programs; </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Evaluates CEO performance results; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Makes the compensation decisions for the CEO; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Approves the compensation program and compensation for Executives; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Reviews and approves corporate incentive goals and objectives relevant to compensation; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Evaluates the competitiveness of each Executive's total compensation; and </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Compensation
Advisory Partners is selected and retained by the Committee to advise on the Executive compensation program. Compensation Advisory Partners also advises the Nominating and Governance
Committee </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>

<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=41,EFW="2241086",CP="PRINCIPAL FINANCIAL GROUP, INC.",DN="1",CHK=58066,FOLIO='38',FILE='DISK124:[20ZAD1.20ZAD41801]DM41801A.;20',USER='CHE106204',CD='31-MAR-2020;21:29' -->
<a name="page_dm41801_1_39"> </a>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font size="2"><a href="#bi41801a_main_toc">Table of Contents</a></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">on
compensation for non-employee Directors (see pages 21-24). Compensation Advisory Partners receives compensation from the Company only for its work in advising these Committees. Compensation
Advisory Partners does not and would not be allowed to perform services for management. The Committee assessed the independence factors in applicable SEC rules and Nasdaq Listing Standards and other
facts and circumstances and concluded that the services performed by Compensation Advisory Partners did not raise any conflict of interest. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">No
member of management, including the CEO, has a role in determining his or her own compensation; and the CEO is not present when the Committee discusses his compensation. The Committee consults with
the independent Directors regarding the CEO's performance and then determines the compensation earned by the CEO for the current year and the CEO's compensation opportunity for the following year. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Each
year the CEO, with input from the Human Resources Department and the compensation consultant, recommends the amount of base salary increase (if any), annual incentive award and long-term
incentive award for Named Executive Officers other than himself. These recommendations are based on the Executive's performance, performance of the business areas for which the Executive is
responsible (if applicable) and other considerations such as retention. The Human Resources Committee reviews these recommendations and approves compensation decisions for Executives. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


The role of the Independent Compensation Consultant &amp; Interaction with Management </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The Human Resources Committee has the sole authority to hire, approve the compensation of and terminate the engagement of the compensation consultant. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
compensation consultant usually conducts a comprehensive review of the Company's Executive compensation program every other year. In the years in which the compensation consultant does not conduct
a compensation study, the Committee makes compensation decisions, in part, on survey data provided by the Human Resources Department and input provided by the compensation consultant. A review of
executive compensation was conducted in 2018. The comprehensive study of Executive compensation conducted by the Committee's compensation consultant reviews all aspects of the design and structure of
the Company's total Executive compensation program, and includes:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Interviews with Executives and Directors to discuss business strategy and the implications for human resources and compensation policy; </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> A competitive review of compensation opportunities for each of the Named Executive Officers compared to the pay opportunities of similarly
situated executives at the Peer Group companies (see below); </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> An analysis to ensure that total share dilution and the economic costs of long-term incentives are reasonable and affordable for the Company;
and </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> A review of Executive compensation plans against potential risks. Compensation Advisory Partners conducted a review of the Company's Executive
compensation plans in 2018 and determined that the Company's Executive compensation programs are well designed, support the Company's business strategy, and do not provide incentives to Executives to
take inappropriate risks. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
compensation consultant:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Attended seven meetings of the Committee in 2019, as requested by the Committee Chair; and </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Reviewed and commented on drafts of the Compensation Discussion &amp; Analysis and related compensation tables for the proxy statement.
</font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Use of Compensation Data </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The Committee reviews the Peer Group of companies it uses to compare Executive compensation as part of the compensation consultant's biennial study. The compensation consultant
recommends an appropriate Peer Group of public, similarly sized, diversified financial services, insurance and asset management companies, considering the Company's and the competitors' strategy, mix
of business and size, as measured primarily by annual revenues, market capitalization and total assets. These companies are the major competitors in one or more of the Company's businesses, but none
represent the exact business mix of the Company. Principal targets compensation for the Named Executive Officers at the median of the compensation of the named executive officers at the Peer Group
companies. The companies in the Peer Group were reviewed in 2018 as part of the compensation review and Eaton Vance and Legg Mason were removed as they are smaller relative to Principal based on
revenue market capitalization and/or operating income. Unum Group was added because it is only slightly smaller than Principal </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>
<div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

width:100%;
margin-left:0%;
">

<!-- end of user-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
</div>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee also uses annual data from third party industry surveys for its compensation decisions<sup>4</sup>. Our Executives participate in the same broad-based employee benefit programs as
other employees. Every two to three years, the Company's non-cash employee benefit programs are compared to a custom peer group representing both proxy peer group members and select employers we
believe we compete for talent with, including several local employers. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Each
year, the Committee reviews the total compensation paid to the Named Executive Officers by reviewing tally sheets, which include base salaries, annual and long-term incentive awards earned,
deferred compensation, outstanding equity awards, benefits, perquisites, and potential payments under various termination scenarios. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee uses this information to analyze the value of compensation actually delivered versus the compensation opportunities established by the Committee. The information also is used in making
compensation and compensation plan design decisions. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->
<a name="h1"></a>2019 Executive Compensation Decisions  </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">In general, Principal's pay philosophy is to target the market median of the Peer Group for an Executive's total compensation, with actual
compensation varying based on performance and tenure. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee made compensation decisions for the Named Executive Officers based on:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The Company's strategic and human resources objectives; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Competitive data for the Peer Group and for a broader group of diversified financial services companies (see Appendix C for a complete
list of these companies); </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Corporate and individual performance on key initiatives; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Economic conditions; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Retirement benefits; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The CEO's compensation recommendations for Named Executive Officers; </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Advice of the Committee's consultant; and </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> How the elements of compensation contribute to and interrelate to total compensation. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee also considers the tax and accounting consequences of each element of compensation. For taxable years through 2017, the Committee tried to maximize the tax deductibility to Principal of
compensation under available exceptions to the application of Section 162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code ("Tax Code"), while simultaneously providing competitive compensation that enhanced our
business objectives. This Tax Code section limits Principal from deducting annual compensation exceeding $1 million for our CEO, CFO and other executive officers and former executive officers
who were among the three most highly compensated executive officers for any year after 2017 ("Covered Employees"). For taxable years prior to 2018, there was an exception to this 162(m) limitation for
performance-based compensation meeting certain criteria, but this exception has generally been repealed for taxable years after 2017 (subject to certain limited grandfathering of compensation payable
pursuant to binding written agreements outstanding on November 2, 2017). The Committee considers the impact of this </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;line-height:1pt;margin-left:18pt;"><font> </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<!-- BLANK LINE TO FORCE PARA -->
   
</font></p><hr align="LEFT" color="#7B7C80" noshade="" size="1.0PT" width="24%"/><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> </font><p></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>(4)</i></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>The surveys used were the McLagan Investment Management survey, Towers Watson U.S. Financial Services Studies Executive Database and the
Towers Watson Diversified Insurance Study of Executive Compensation. The names of the companies participating in these surveys are included in
Appendix C.</i></font></dd></dl>

<a name="page_dm41801_1_41"> </a>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font size="2"><a href="#bi41801a_main_toc">Table of Contents</a></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">change
in the applicable federal income tax laws as it makes and implements decisions regarding compensation that will be payable after 2017. Tax deductibility affects the net cost of the compensation
payable by Principal to Covered Employees and is one factor to be considered in designing competitive and effective compensation programs. Other factors, such as the need to provide our senior
executives compensation that is competitive with that payable in the marketplace, that retains their services and that provides appropriate incentives to achieve our business plans and objectives, may
cause the Committee to continue to provide compensation opportunities that are generally consistent with those previously provided, despite the probability that at least some of the compensation
payable to some or all of the Covered Employees will not be tax deductible after 2017. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
charts below show the 2019 target total compensation for our Named Executive Officers as well as the proportion of their compensation tied to Company performance. Most compensation paid to our
Named Executive Officers is variable and at risk, linked to meeting our short-term and long-term financial and strategic goals and to the performance of the Company's stock over time. </font></p>

<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="dm41801_base_salary"> </a>
<a name="toc_dm41801_3"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Base Salary    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">When determining base salary for each Executive, the Committee considers the Peer Group median for comparable executive positions as well as
the survey data referenced above, the Executive's performance and work experience, the importance of the position to the Company and how difficult it would be to replace the Executive. There were no
changes to base salary for the Named Executive Officers in 2019. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->
<a name="dm1"></a>Annual Incentive Compensation  </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Effective January 1, 2019, Named Executive Officers participate in the Principal Financial Group Incentive Pay Plan (PrinPay Plan), the
Company's broad-based annual incentive compensation plan for employees. Awards are calculated based on eligible earnings during the plan year. The PrinPay Plan links annual incentive pay to individual
employee results and overall company performance and profitability. Annual financial and non-financial goals for company performance and individual performance are set. After establishing the company
score, an employee's individual goal performance is used to determine the individual score an employee receives. The corporate component emphasizes the importance of overall corporate results and
includes non-GAAP operating earnings and a variety of other financial and non-financial metrics. The Human Resources Committee may also consider factors that could not have been anticipated when
corporate goals were established and adjust the corporate score up or down. </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>
<div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">

*display:block;

<td style="font-family:arial;
" width="50.00%">
<p style="font-family:arial;display:none;">​</p>
<div style="width:50.00%;
"></div></td>
<td style="font-family:arial;
" width="12.0pt">
<p style="font-family:arial;display:none;">​</p>
<div style="width:12.0pt;
"></div></td>
<td style="font-family:arial;
" width="108.00pt">
<p style="font-family:arial;display:none;">​</p>
<div style="width:108.00pt;
"></div></td>
<td style="font-family:arial;

<div style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:12%;">
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>(1)</i></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>Mr. Dunbar's pro-rated target for 2018 was 174% (80% for January 1, 2018 through September 14, 2018 and 400% for
September 15, 2018 through December 31, 2018).</i></font><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>(2)</i></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><i>Mr. Halter's pro-rated target for 2018 was 332% (325% for January 1, 2018 through September 14, 2018 and 350% for
September 15, 2018 through December 31, 2018).</i></font></dd></dl>
</div>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">In
establishing the target award opportunity for Messrs. Houston, Dunbar, Halter and Valdés and Ms. Strable-Soethout, the Committee considered the median incentive targets
for comparable executive positions in the Peer Group companies, as well as the survey data referenced above. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Performance Goal Setting and Measurement Process </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> September:</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    The Board meets to review the Company's long-term strategy. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> November:</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    The CEO, CFO and Division Presidents recommend preliminary financial goals for the Company and business units and strategic initiatives for
the next
year. The Finance Committee reviews the proposed goals, underlying assumptions of the goals and initiatives, key drivers of financial performance, trends and business opportunities and advises the
Board and Human Resources Committee on the appropriateness of the financial goals. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b> February:</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">    The Committee reviews and approves the final goals for the Company, the CEO and the other Executives with input from the Finance Committee
and Board
based on prior year end financial results. All employees develop individual performance goals with their leaders that support the Company's goals. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Final Annual Incentive Pay Award Determination </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">In determining final awards for PrinPay participants, the Committee uses the following approach: </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Step
1: Review Operating Earnings goal versus Plan to determine initial award funding. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Step
2: Determine final PrinPay company score based on a review of performance against goals across multiple dimensions included in the Company's annual Balanced Scorecard (e.g., Financial
Measures, Customer Measures, Internal Measures and Learning and Growth Measures, etc.) </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>
<div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Step 3: Determine the individual performance modifier as shown below: </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#009CCC" size="2">
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Individual Performance Modifier </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The Individual Performance Modifier in the PrinPay Plan is used as a multiplier and is based on performance compared to 2019 goals. The Committee addressed each Named Executive
Officer's performance against the individual performance objectives identified and approved individual performance modifier payouts as shown below: </font></p>

<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Executives
may defer annual awards into the Excess Plan, as illustrated in the footnote to the Non-Equity Incentive Compensation column of the Summary Compensation Table, on pages 49-50. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="dq41801_long-term_incentive_compensation"> </a>
<a name="toc_dq41801_1"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Long-term Incentive Compensation    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
long-term incentive compensation program is designed to align the interests of Executives and shareholders. The compensation the Executives receive reflects the degree to which multiyear financial
objectives are achieved and shareholder value is increased. The long-term focus of the compensation programs supports the Company's businesses, for which long-term performance is critical, such as
retirement products, life insurance and asset management. The long-term incentive compensation program also encourages collaboration among Executives in pursuing corporate wide goals. </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=46,EFW="2241086",CP="PRINCIPAL FINANCIAL GROUP, INC.",DN="1",CHK=43282,FOLIO='43',FILE='DISK124:[20ZAD1.20ZAD41801]DQ41801A.;19',USER='CHE109696',CD='31-MAR-2020;21:31' -->
<a name="page_dq41801_1_44"> </a>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font size="2"><a href="#bi41801a_main_toc">Table of Contents</a></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee establishes a target long-term incentive award opportunity for each Named Executive Officer, stated as a percentage of each Named Executive Officer's base salary, based on Peer Group and
survey data, and on the advice of its independent compensation consultant. The Committee uses the following factors to adjust the target award and determine the actual award to be granted to each
Named Executive Officer ("Award Granted"):</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Current competitive market data; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The Named Executive Officer's past
performance; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The Named Executive Officer's current compensation; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Retention concerns; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Tenure in role; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt>
<dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The importance of the Named Executive Officer to the Company over the long term; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The potential impact the Named
Executive Officer could have on the Company's results; and </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> The Executive's performance relative to the Named Executive Officer's peers within the
Company. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
compensation ultimately received by Named Executive Officers may vary considerably from the grant date fair value of the Award Granted, due to the Company's performance and changes in share price
that occur after the grant. </font></p>
<div style="display:none;*display:block;margin-top:-4pt;"></div>
<div style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:75%;margin-left:12%;">
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"100%" -->
<!-- User-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
<div align="CENTER"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
<tbody><tr style="line-height:0pt;"><!-- TABLE COLUMN WIDTHS SET -->
<td style="font-family:arial;" width="100.00%"><div style="width:100.00%;"></div></td>

</div>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Executives'
long-term compensation is provided as non-qualified stock options and PSUs, which each represent 50% of the total grant date fair value. PSUs entitle the Executive to earn shares of Common
Stock if certain levels of performance are achieved. The Committee uses stock options as part of the long-term incentive program because options are an effective way to link an Executive's
compensation to changes in shareholder value. The weighting is not based on a specific formula or algorithm and is intended to create a balance between the achievement of specific operating objectives
and changes in shareholder value based on the Committee's judgment, which may change from time to time. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>Stock options</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> have a ten-year term and an exercise price equal to the closing price on the date of grant. Stock options vest in three equal annual
installments starting on the first anniversary of the grant date. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><b>After a threshold goal is achieved or exceeded<sup>(5)</sup>, PSUs</b></font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> vest based on continued service and achieving an average ROE and Pre-Tax Return on
Net Revenue<sup>(6)</sup>, each weighted 50%, over a three-year period (with each three-year period treated as a "Performance Cycle"). </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">In
addition to achieving the ROE measure, there is also a Book Value per Share<sup>(7)</sup> threshold tied to the ROE performance measure, which is used to prevent the Company from achieving ROE
by inappropriately reducing equity. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;line-height:1pt;margin-left:18pt;"> <font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">
<!-- BLANK LINE TO FORCE PARA -->
   
</font></p><hr align="LEFT" color="#7B7C80" noshade="" size="1.0PT" width="24%"/><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"> </font><p></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(5)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">For
the 2019 PSUs, the performance threshold is met if either of the following goals is met:</font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Three-year average operating ROE(5) of 7.5%; or </font> <font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">$2 billion cumulative pretax operating income ("OI") </font></dd></dl>
<ul>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Operating ROE is defined as Non-GAAP Operating Earnings divided by common equity excluding accumulated other comprehensive income, other than foreign currency
translation adjustment. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Pre-tax operating income is defined as income from continuing operations before income taxes per the audited Consolidated Statements of Operations less net
realized/unrealized capital gains (losses), less preferred stock dividends declared, less net income attributable to noncontrolling interest. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Average operating ROE was selected because it reflects the efficient use of Company capital in generating profits. Average Pre-tax Return on Net Revenue was
selected as a measure because it is common among asset management peers and reflects the efficient use of Company expenditures in generating profits. </font></p>
</ul>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(6)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Pre-tax
return on net revenue is defined as pre-tax Non-GAAP Operating Earnings is divided by net revenue. Net revenue is defined as total operating revenue less
benefits, claims, and settlement expenses less dividends to policyholders.
<br/><br/></font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(7)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Book
value per Share is defined as total ending common equity excluding other comprehensive income divided by the number of common shares outstanding end of
year.</font></dd></dl>

<td align="RIGHT" style="line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #009CCC 1.8pt;" valign="BOTTOM"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​ <!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"border-bottom:solid #009CCC 1.8pt;" -->
<font></font></td>

<br/></font> <font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">If neither the ROE nor the OI threshold performance<br/>
objective is met, </font><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"><b><u>no PSUs</u></b></font><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"> will<br/>
be earned or paid out.<br/>

<br/>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(1)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">Straight
line interpolation is used to determine awards for performance between threshold and target and between target and maximum. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The Book Value per Share threshold tied to ROE performance measure: </font></p>
<ul>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">If
the average Book Value per Share is between $42.80 and $47.65, the ROE performance score will be reduced by 50%. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">If
the average Book Value per Share is below $42.80, the ROE performance score will be reduced to 0%. </font></p>
</ul>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
PSUs granted in 2020 for the 2020-2022 Performance Cycle will vest based on performance scales for two-year average ROE and Pre-Tax Return on Net Revenue, each weighted 50% over the performance
period. Payout on the ROE metric will be modified based on a two-year Book Value per Share versus threshold goals. The change in the performance period to two years is due to accounting changes
effective January 1, 2022 for publicly traded companies which may result in significant variability of reported earnings each year for companies with significant life insurance and annuity
businesses. For the 2020-2022 Performance Cycle, PSUs will continue to vest at the end of the three-year Performance Cycle. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_timing_of_stock_option__ds402421"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_1"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Timing of Stock Option Awards and Other Equity Incentives    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Annual
grants of stock options and PSUs for Principal Executives are determined by the Committee at its February meeting which occurs following the release of the prior year's results. The Committee
formalized its long-standing practices by adopting a policy in 2006 regarding granting stock options and other equity awards. Under this policy, the grant date for all stock options and other
stock-based awards shall never be earlier than the date of approval, and shall be:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> For all annual awards to Executives, the date of approval by the Committee; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> For new employees and promotions, the later of the date of approval or the employee's hire/promotion date; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> In the event of an award connected
with an established stock program for non-Executives, the later of the date of approval or the grant date
established by the stock program; and </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> For any other awards, the date of approval. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_benefits"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_2"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Benefits    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Named Executive Officers participate in Principal Life's broad-based employee benefits program, including:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> A qualified pension plan (except Messrs. Dunbar and Halter<sup>(9)</sup>); </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> A 401(k) plan; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Group health, dental, vision and disability coverage and life insurance; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
</font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> A discounted employee stock purchase plan; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Flexible time off; and </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Flexible spending account plans. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Principal
Life also offers all Named Executive Officers (except Messrs. Dunbar and Halter) a non-qualified defined contribution plan ("Excess Plan") and a defined benefit non-qualified
retirement plan ("NQDB"). These benefits are offered to attract and retain talent and provide long-term financial security to employees. The NQDB helps the Company attract midcareer Executives and
retain Executives by providing competitive retirement benefits. The NQDB is coordinated with the qualified pension plan and is designed to restore benefits that otherwise would accrue to Executives in
the absence of Tax Code limitations on the qualified pension plan. The narrative to the Pension Benefits Table on pages 54-56 provides additional information about the NQDB and the qualified
pension plan. Principal Life maintains the Excess Plan to help attract and retain Executives by allowing Executives to save for retirement and to provide matching contributions on those savings,
without regard to the limitations imposed by </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;line-height:1pt;margin-left:18pt;"><font> </font> <font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">
<!-- BLANK LINE TO FORCE PARA -->
   
</font></p><hr align="LEFT" color="#7B7C80" noshade="" size="1.0PT" width="24%"/><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;"> </font><p></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-9pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">(9)</font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" style="font-size:8pt;line-height:9pt;">On
January 1, 2010, Executives in the Company's asset management operations stopped participating in the qualified pension plan, NQDB Plan or Excess Plan as
these are not common benefits for executives in that industry. This change also applied to other investment professionals.</font></dd></dl>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=48,EFW="2241086",CP="PRINCIPAL FINANCIAL GROUP, INC.",DN="1",CHK=407550,FOLIO='45',FILE='DISK124:[20ZAD1.20ZAD41801]DS41801A.;22',USER='CHE109696',CD='31-MAR-2020;23:22' -->
<a name="page_ds41801_1_46"> </a>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font size="2"><a href="#bi41801a_main_toc">Table of Contents</a></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">the
Tax Code on 401(k) plans. The narrative to the Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table on page 55 provides additional information about the Excess Plan. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
value of the retirement and savings plans for Non-Grandfathered Participants (see page 55) is targeted to be, in the aggregate, slightly above the median of diversified financial services
companies because a large portion of the Company's business centers on the sale of retirement products. The defined benefit pension plan for Grandfathered Choice Participants (see page 54) has
a market value above the median and the 401(k) plan match for Grandfathered Choice Participants is below market median. These benefits were also originally designed to be slightly above market median
to attract and retain employees. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">All
other benefits are targeted at market median in the aggregate, which supports the Company's benefit strategy and aids in attracting and retaining talent. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_change_of_control_and_separation_pay"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_3"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Change of Control and Separation Pay    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee believes it is in the best interests of Principal and its shareholders to:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Assure that Principal will have the continued service of its Executives; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Reduce the distraction of these Executives that would result from the personal uncertainties caused by a pending or threatened Change of
Control; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Encourage the Executives' full attention and dedication to Principal; and </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Provide the Executives with compensation and benefits upon a termination related to a Change of Control that are competitive with those of
similar businesses. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">For
these reasons, Principal has entered into Change of Control Employment Agreements with each of the Executives. These agreements would help align the financial interests of management with the
Company, particularly when the acquisition would result in termination of the Executive's employment. These Change of Control Employment Agreements are based on market practice and do not affect other
components of the Executives' compensation. When entering into these agreements, the Committee reviewed survey data and practices of other public insurance and financial services companies. The
Committee continues to review market practices in this area for potential changes in these agreements. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">All
benefits provided to the Executives upon a Change of Control are paid after both a Change of Control and qualifying termination of employment have occurred (sometimes referred to as a double
trigger), except that the then current value of the Executive's Excess Plan and NQDB will be paid upon a Change of Control to ensure that the value of those plans is not reduced if the Company is
sold. These agreements do not provide excise tax gross ups. See pages 59-61 for details. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Company has a severance plan to provide benefits to employees whose employment is terminated by the Company due to a reorganization or reduction in the workforce. Additional payments may be
permitted in some circumstances as a result of negotiations with Executives, particularly when Principal requests additional covenants from the Executives. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_stock_ownership_guidelines"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_4"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Stock Ownership Guidelines    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Executives are required to own a meaningful amount of stock in the Company to ensure their interests are aligned with the shareholders'
interests and with the Company's long-term performance. Once the Executive achieves the required stock ownership level based on market value, the ownership requirement remains at the number of shares
owned at the time, regardless of subsequent changes in stock price or salary. Upon promotion, the Executive is required to meet the next level of stock ownership. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Until
the ownership guideline is met, Executives are required to retain a portion of the "net profit shares" resulting from equity based long-term incentive plan grants. Net profit shares are the
shares remaining after payment of the option exercise price and taxes owed at time of exercise, vesting of RSUs or earn out of performance shares. Effective January 1, 2019, ownership
requirements increased from 5 times to 7 times base salary for the Chairman and 3 times to 4 times base salary for Division Presidents and Executive Vice Presidents. Executives must meet the </font></p>
<font color="??????" style="display:none;">​</font>
<div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">new
requirements within five years of the date of the change. The percentage of net profit shares that must be retained until ownership requirements are met are shown below: </font></p>
<div style="display:none;*display:block;margin-top:-4pt;"></div>

<font></font></td>
<td style="white-space:nowrap;line-height:0pt;font-size:1.5pt;font-family:arial;border-bottom:solid #009CCC 1.0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font>​<font>

</div>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">All
Named Executive Officers comply with these guidelines. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_hedging_policy"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_5"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Hedging Policy    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Principal
prohibits all employees, including Named Executive Officers, from purchasing any Principal securities on margin (except for exercising stock options); engaging in short sales or trading in
any put or call options; and purchasing, directly or indirectly, any financial instrument (including prepaid variable forward contracts, equity swaps, collars and exchange funds) that is designed to
hedge or offset any decrease in the market value of Principal securities. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_repricing_policy"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_6"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Repricing Policy    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Principal
has not repriced underwater stock options and we will not do so without shareholder approval. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_claw_back_policy"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_7"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Claw Back Policy    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee has adopted a compensation recovery policy that applies to Executives. Principal can recover any incentive compensation if the amount of the compensation was based on achievement of
financial results that were subsequently restated if the Committee decides that the Executive engaged in fraud or intentional
misconduct that caused the restatement of the Company's financial statements, and if the amount of the Executive's incentive compensation or equity award would have been lower had the financial
results been properly reported. Principal can also cancel or recover incentive compensation, received in the event of either reputational or financial harm to the Company that arises directly or
indirectly from an Executive's misconduct, gross negligence, misfeasance or nonfeasance. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_trading_policy"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_8"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Trading Policy    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Principal
prohibits Directors and employees, including Executives, from:</font></p>
<dl compact="">
<dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Purchasing Principal securities "on margin" (i.e., with the proceeds of a loan from a brokerage firm when the loan is secured by
Principal securities), except for the exercise of employee stock options. </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Short sales; </font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Trading in put or call options; and </font><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">
</font></dd><dt style="font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"></font></dt><dd style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"> Purchasing, directly or through a designee, any financial instrument (including prepaid variable forward contracts, equity swaps, collars and
exchange funds) that is designed to hedge or offset any decrease in the market value of Principal securities. </font></dd></dl>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_gross-up_policy"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_9"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Gross-Up Policy    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Executives
do not receive any income tax gross-ups, except that all employees, including Executives, receive an income tax gross-up in connection with benefits provided with relocation. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify;margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2"><a name="ds41801_human_resources_committee_report"> </a>
<a name="toc_ds41801_10"> </a></font> <font color="#009CCC" size="2"><b>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:0pt;text-indent:-0pt;" -->


Human Resources Committee Report    <br/> </b></font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">The
Committee has reviewed and discussed the foregoing Compensation Discussion and Analysis required by Item 402(b) of Regulation S-K with management, and, based on such review and
discussion, the Committee recommended to the Board that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this Proxy Statement. </font></p>
<p style="font-family:arial;text-align:justify"><font color="#7B7C80" size="2">Betsy
J. Bernard, Chair<br/>
Michael T. Dan<br/></font></p>
